      <slide>
        <title>Motivating Questions</title>

<definition>
  <statement>
    <p>
      For an object moving according to position function <m>s(t)</m>, the <alert>average velocity</alert> on the interval <m>[a,a+h]</m> is given by
      <me>
        AV_{[a,a+h]}= \frac{s(a+h)-s(a)}{h}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>
  With the notion of a limit, we can now understand <em>instantaneous velocity</em>.
</p>

<definition>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The <alert>instantaneous velocity</alert> at <m>a</m> is the limit of average velocity <m>AV_{[a,a+h]}</m> as <m>h \rightarrow 0</m>.
      That is,
      <me>
        IV_{t=a}= \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}AV_{[a,a+h]}= \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{s(a+h)-s(a)}{h}.
      </me>
    </p>

    Note: For a general function <m>f</m> that does not describe an objectâ€™s position, we can 
    similarly define the <alert>average rate of change</alert> of <m>f</m> and <alert>instantaneous rate of change</alert> of <m>f</m>.
  </statement>
</definition>


      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>The Derivative of a Function at a Point</title>
        
  <p> We want to find how the volume of a balloon changes as it is filled with air.
We know <m>\displaystyle V(r) = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^{3}</m>, where <m>r</m> is the radius in inches and <m>V(r)</m> is the volume is in cubic inches.
The expression <m>\displaystyle \frac{V(3)-V(1)}{3-1}</m> represents the average rate of change of </p>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      the radius with respect to the volume when the radius changes from 1 inch to 3 inches.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      the radius with respect to the volume when the volume changes from 1 cubic inch to 3 cubic inches.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      the volume with respect to the radius when the radius changes from 1 inch to 3 inches.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      the volume with respect to the radius when the volume changes from 1 cubic inch to 3 cubic inches.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>

